observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the City Mayor direct the:
a. Inventory Committee to conduct complete physical count of all inventory items;
b. CGSO and CAO to reconcile the balances of their respective records of Inventories;
c. CAO to record the purchases of supplies and materials to inventory accounts instead of outright expense and comply with the perpetual inventory system in maintaining inventory records to properly account for additions to and subtractions from inventory; and
d. CGSO to prepare the RSMI for the issued inventories totaling P788,890.00 and submit to the CAO for the recognition of expense using prior period adjustment.

We recommended that the City Mayor direct the:
a. City Engineer and other concerned City officials to investigate and identify the cause/s of the delay in the completion and implementation of the project and ensure that appropriate charges, penalties and sanctions are meted out to the person/s who may be found responsible and/or accountable therefor;
b. City Engineer and other concerned City officials to make the necessary documents, in violation of Section 4(6) of PD No. 1445;
c. City Accountant to facilitate the submission of the lacking documents to the Audit Team to prevent the issuance of a Notice of Suspension of the payments already made to the Contractor; and
d. City Accountant to ensure that further disbursement of funds related to the project are net of liquidated damages and other applicable penalties imposed under Item 8 of Annex E of the RIRR of RA No. 9184 and Section 39.3 of the same RIRR and supported with complete documents.

We recommended that the City Mayor direct the:
• City Administrator to provide to the Audit Team the Distribution List of the school supplies and erasable books worth P1,184,027.50 and P739,603.15, respectively, duly acknowledged by the actual beneficiaries/recipients to attest to the veracity of the disbursements and avoid the issuance of Notice of Suspension. Henceforth, all supplies and materials distributed to intended beneficiaries be properly documented to ensure that the resources of the government are managed and utilized in accordance with the established rules and regulations;
• Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) and other concerned officials to provide/submit justifiable reasons for the inconsistencies between the dates and reference numbers in the purchase of school supplies worth P1,184,027.50 for evaluation by the Audit Team, otherwise, the payment made may be suspended/disallowed in audit;
• City Social Welfare and Development Officer to be the one in charge of determining and requesting for the appropriate instructional materials for day care children to avoid wastage of government funds;
• City General Services Officer to be in charge of the acceptance of all purchases of goods as property custodianship, recording and maintaining of property records are among the functions of his Office;
• City Accountant and the General Services Officer to comply with the accounting and reporting requirements prescribed under COA Circular No. 2015-009 dated December 1, 2015 to ensure the correctness and reliability of the financial reporting of the City; and
• City Accountant to draw a Journal Entry Voucher to adjust the overstatement of the PPE and government equity accounts each by P1,989,250.00.

We recommended that the City Mayor limit the hiring of Job Order personnel to what is prudent and necessary in the exigencies of the service, and direct:

the OIC-Human Resource Management Officer to establish a sound system of control in hiring the JO personnel which should basically include the following procedures:

require the applicants to submit Birth or Marriage Certificates, NBI or Police Clearance and other valid proof of identity for the job being applied for;

require applicants to undergo interview and other basic screening process;

evaluate the performance of JO personnel and determine at the end of the contract period whether there is still necessity of renewing the job orders; and

certification that the services rendered by JO personnel cannot be provided by the regular or present personnel of the City Government.

the OIC-City Accountant to ensure that payment of wages of Job Order (JO) personnel are supported with Accomplishment Report and Contracts detailing the works to be accomplished to prove the validity and regularity of the transactions.  Likewise, always check the computation of payrolls to prevent excess claims;

the Payees and/or officials responsible for the excess payment and double claims to refund the amount of P50,000.00 and P24,000.00 or a total of P74,000.00;

the Disbursing Officer to make sure that payments were made directly to the claimants by affixing their signatures in the payroll; and

the OIC – HRMO in coordination with the Department Heads of the City to submit validated justification with supporting documents, for further evaluation by the Audit Team, on the necessity on the hiring of 1,624 JO personnel in CY 2015.

We recommended that the City Mayor direct the City Budget Officer, OIC-City Accountant and Treasurer to consider the following measures:

exercise utmost diligence in the disposition of government funds;

limit expenses to actual income received;

make sure that obligations incurred and continuing appropriations are always supported by funds available for such purpose/s;

ensure that inter-agency payables and other current liabilities that are considered as trust receipts are spent only for the specific purpose for which they were created or received and/or remitted to concerned agencies within the prescribed period;

see to it that supplemental budgets, if any, are backed up by additional source of fund; and



adopt effective/efficient collection strategy for Real Property Tax Receivable of P144,471,057.25 by granting tax relief through compromise agreement with the authority of the Sangguniang Panlungsod and/or initiate remedies by administrative action through levy on real property and sale of real property by public auction or by judicial action as embodied under City Ordinance No. 2011-02, otherwise known as the 2012 Revenue Code of Trece Martires City.

We recommended that the Sangguniang Panlungsod provide clear policy on the amount to be granted for each type of assistance for uniformity purposes and to ensure that funds are released to the less privileged and in dire need residents of Trece Martires City.

We also recommended that the City Mayor direct:

the OIC-City Accountant to submit the supporting documents for donations/financial assistance amounting to P10,145,997.78 to determine the propriety and validity of the claims.  Henceforth, advise him to stop processing claims with incomplete or inappropriate documentation, and those expenses appearing to be for private purposes. In addition, direct him to refrain from charging donations to Other Payables account;

the City Budget Officer to refrain from charging financial assistance/donations to other expenses/accounts and prior year’s expenses against current appropriation;

the City Social Welfare and Development Officer to properly screen the applicants for donation/financial assistance for emergency assistance program so that deserving and less privileged constituents are given priority in the grant of assistance. Likewise, ensure the authenticity and completeness of the submitted documents during the assessment/evaluation of claims; and

the City Administrator to cause the investigation of the concerned employees/person/s responsible for the processing and approval of claims supported with documents of doubtful authenticity.  Initiate the filing of appropriate charges, if warranted.
